3. Cluster Restore Script (From S3 Backup)
Below is a basic shell script to restore etcd from a specific S3 backup. This script should be run on a control-plane node in a disaster recovery scenario.

Note: This will overwrite existing etcd data.

bash
Copy
Edit
#!/bin/bash

BACKUP_NAME="backup-2025-05-01-00-00.tar.gz"
S3_BUCKET="etcd-backups"
REGION="us-west-1"

# Step 1: Download the backup from S3
aws s3 cp s3://$S3_BUCKET/$BACKUP_NAME /var/lib/etcd/$BACKUP_NAME --region $REGION

# Step 2: Extract backup
tar -xzf /var/lib/etcd/$BACKUP_NAME -C /var/lib/etcd/

# Step 3: Stop etcd
sudo systemctl stop etcd

# Step 4: Restore etcd from snapshot
ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl snapshot restore /var/lib/etcd/snapshot.db \
  --name <node-name> \
  --initial-cluster <node-name>=https://<IP>:2380 \
  --initial-cluster-token etcd-cluster-1 \
  --initial-advertise-peer-urls https://<IP>:2380 \
  --data-dir /var/lib/etcd

# Step 5: Restart etcd
sudo systemctl start etcd
Replace <node-name> and <IP> with your actual control plane details.

4. OpenShift Recommendations for ETCD Backup
OpenShift provides a set of best practices for etcd backups:

Schedule regular backups (at least every 12 hours).

Store backups off-cluster, preferably in S3 or another object storage.

Automate backup creation and retention policies using CronJobs.

Encrypt sensitive data in backups.

Test restores regularly in non-production clusters to ensure DR readiness.

Do not place etcd backups on local disks only.

Use static IPs for control plane nodes to avoid IP mismatch issues during restore.

For more details: OpenShift Backup and Restore Docs

