4. Cluster Restore Script (From S3 Backup)
Below is a sample restore script for etcd. Use only in disaster recovery:

bash
Copy
Edit
#!/bin/bash

BACKUP_NAME="etcd-backup.tar.gz"
S3_BUCKET="etcd-backups"
REGION="us-west-1"

# Step 1: Download the backup
aws s3 cp s3://$S3_BUCKET/$BACKUP_NAME /tmp/$BACKUP_NAME --region $REGION

# Step 2: Extract
tar -xzf /tmp/$BACKUP_NAME -C /tmp/

# Step 3: Restore snapshot
ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl snapshot restore /tmp/etcd-backup/snapshot.db \
  --name <node-name> \
  --initial-cluster <node-name>=https://<ip>:2380 \
  --initial-cluster-token etcd-cluster-1 \
  --initial-advertise-peer-urls https://<ip>:2380 \
  --data-dir /var/lib/etcd

# Step 4: Copy static manifests and certs
sudo cp -a /tmp/etcd-backup/manifests /etc/kubernetes/
sudo cp -a /tmp/etcd-backup/static-pod-resources /etc/kubernetes/

# Step 5: Restart kubelet (which restarts etcd)
sudo systemctl restart kubelet
5. OpenShift ETCD Backup Best Practices
OpenShift recommends the following:

Use automated CronJobs for scheduled backups.

Store backups off-cluster, preferably in S3, GCS, or Azure Blob.

Encrypt your backups.

Backup frequency: At least twice daily.

Test restores periodically on non-production clusters.

Back up manifests and certs, not just the etcd snapshot.

Document your DR process and store access securely.

More official guidance:
OpenShift Docs – Backup and Restore

